5 years ago I sat on the edge of the sofa staring at the big box of chocolates.

I wanted one but I didnâ€™t know the calories. I googled, I looked on my fitness pal but nothing was definite enough to settle my mind.

I sat in torment for half an hour then decided I was going in.

I picked out 2 penguins & ate them, it tasted so good, for a min I felt ok, but then it started.
-
â€you didnâ€™t the caloriesâ€ â€œgo look in the mirror you got fatâ€ â€œyou might as well eat the whole box.â€ I went into panic I didnâ€™t want to binge & deal with feeling sick & mind fogged so I had to distract myself & I needed to burn calories so I grabbed my trainers & went for a run.

I remember thinking â€œwell you didnâ€™t binge this time but you still ate bad foodâ€ felt as guilty & stressed as I did after a full jar of Nutella & cereal binge.

I had competed 2months ago in another attempt to try & feel happy & like I was good enough.

After months of restrictive dieting, I was struggling to regain any kind of normality around my relationship with food,

Food was no longer just food I saw it only as calories & they all had the potential to make me fat.

Food had become my number one enemy.

I lived in a tormented headspace of scarcity & deprivation which would often lead to binging & a constant feeling of guilt, shame & fear of getting fat so I would restrict and overtrain.

That Christmas to the outsider it looked like I had a joyous time but inside it was a different story.

After some deep delve work to change the relationship I have with myself this isnâ€™t my life anymore, I am at peace with me so I can enjoy Christmas & all it has to offer without going OTT so I feel like crap & without feeling guilty.

My journey showed me that if you have a skew whiff relationship with food or alcohol then itâ€™s never just about them.

They are just the bandaid to cope with whatâ€™s really going on.

And until you start feeling the feels youâ€™re trying to avoid you canâ€™t transform yourself & that's the truth.

"We are what we repeatedly do." This simple thought by Aristotle has helped me overcome procrastination, fear, laziness and plenty of the other self-limiting beliefs I've told myself to avoid the prospect of pain.

Want to be a writer? Are you writing? Want a better physique? Are you working out? Want better grades? Are you studying? Want to become an entrepreneur? Do you have a plan of action?

Success comes in small steps. That extra rep in the gym. That extra cold call. It's the little decisions that add up over time.

Final thought: In my college Art History class I had to come up with a 3-D art project that represented a famous artist. I decided I would recreate Andy Warhol's Campbell's soup can by duplicating it in the form of a cake.

I spent several hours grocery shopping, gathering ingredients, mixing batter, different colored icings, and eventually baking the cake. It wasn't until I began to put the finishing touches on it that people began to notice.

Classmates wanted to taste it. Neighboring professors came over to check it out.

Random students stopped me to chat.

All this made me realize one thing â€” people don't care about the hard work; most of the time they won't even notice it, but they do recognize and respect the results.

Bake your cake. Do the work. And enjoy your success.
